author/description: Too late to discover the 🌍, too early to explore ✨, just in time to expand consciousness 🧠 @Mystic__VC. Did crypto & skincare, now own nightclubs & make 🎥 🍿
text:
Why I believe Trump will win, we’ll likely know the winner by 11pm tomorrow, and it’s (sadly) a good thing:

Why he will win:

– He’s polling his best ever and he typically outperforms polls

– Supporting Trump has been destigmatized 
        -Anecdotal, but for the first time ever, people regularly express shock that I’m not a Trump supporter (and I live outside of most filter bubbles)
        -His nonsense has become normalized
        –He has much broader support from tech and corporate America than before. 

–Kamala is a terrible candidate who doesn’t stand for anything, is uninspiring, and feels to many like the embodiment of everything wrong with establishment politics. 

–Democrats have alienated too many voters with identity politics and many Jews for their stances on Israel  

–The enthusiasm for Kamala/the fear of Trump isn’t great enough. 

–As a founder of Augur and first investor in @Polymarket you better believe I believe in the markets 🤣

Why we might know the results as soon as tomorrow:

–If Kamala loses the east coast swing states PA, NC, and GA, the election is over, even if she wins every swing state to the west. 

–Vote counting operations are going to be a lot tighter/smoother given the chaos Trump created last time. 

–If Kamala loses PA it’s because she didn’t pick Josh Shapiro as VP and shame on her for that. 

–If Trump loses PA, I wouldn’t discredit it being due to alienating 500k Puerto Ricans there due to the MSG rally (I say that as someone who lives in PR.)

Why this all sadly may be a good thing:

–Most cynically, I’m terrified what happens if Kamala wins in just about any case, but certainly if the election is close or fairly contested. Jan 6 was just a teaser.

–The Dems don’t deserve this win, and need to regroup and realign to the center where they once represented the majority of Americans. 

–Trump won’t last four years, and JD Vance is the most intellectually impressive politician I’ve seen on the national stage since Obama, despite having some abhorrent social views. 

–Trump’s cast of centrist oddballs like Tulsi, Musk, RFK, Vivek-ish could actually do cool stuff if empowered. I’m tired of partisan politics. 

–The markets are going to react incredibly well to a Trump win (see my last tweet)

Conclusion
It’s a sad state of affairs and I’m glad I’m disqualified from voting in this election, but regardless of what happens, it really doesn’t feel like the end of the world. Kamala wouldn’t accomplish much and Trump has the potential to fulfill some cool promises, but also likely have his worst instincts be moderated by those he appears to be surrounding himself with. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

text:
On the eve of the 2024 presidential election, Vice President Kamala Harris holds a 4-point lead over former President Donald Trump among likely voters nationally, according to the latest PBS News/NPR/Marist poll. Harris has the support of 51% of likely voters to Trump’s 47% – a lead just outside the poll’s 3.5-point margin of error.

A little more than half of independents support the Republican nominee, a 5-point lead over Harris.

“It has been and remains a close election,” said Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public Opinion. “As far as the popular vote is concerned, it's hers to lose.”

The 2024 campaign has been shaped by dramatic events unlike any other election year in modern American history: the sitting president and presumptive Democratic nominee withdrawing from the race less than four months before Election Day; the first woman of color nominated as a major party candidate; two assassination attempts on the Republican nominee; and the same nominee convicted on 34 felony charges.

Among those who have already voted, Harris leads Trump 56% to 42%. But with voters who have yet to cast ballots, 53% plan to vote for Trump; while 45% support Harris, according to the poll.

Likely voters surveyed in this poll greatly resemble the 2020 electorate, which backed President Joe Biden with 51% of the popular vote to Trump’s 47%.

“We've gone through all of this to get back to … pretty much where you ended up four years ago,” Miringoff said. “We'll see if the Electoral College mirrors that.”

author/description: Core Contributor responsible for Operations at @ReformDAO | 7 year active crypto mfer | Market making & tokenomics insight
text:
$BTC and the (upcoming) elections means…👇

Historically, we’ve seen $BTC climb significantly after past elections. While that might not mean a direct correlation, Trump’s pro-crypto stance and his policy proposals could act as a strong catalyst if he comes out on top. His win would likely send a clear signal to institutions, potentially easing regulatory pressure and inviting more capital into the space, adding fuel to a post-election rally.

But what if Kamala wins? We’d likely see an initial dip in $BTC, with alts following as market sentiment reacts to this outcome. While this might shake the market in the short term, the long-term impact isn’t that dramatic (it might not exist at all IMO). Plenty of capital is currently sitting on the sidelines, held back by election uncertainty. Once the outcome is clear, that cash is likely to start flowing in, regardless of the victor, as investors seek more stability.

In either case, the election outcome will set the tone for crypto's regulatory landscape, but the broader momentum behind $BTC remains strong.

author/description: Lead politics presenter, Sky News. “Fuelled by canteen hash browns” - the Sunday Times. Watch the Politics Hub with Sophy Ridge 7pm Mon-Thurs
text:
The world awaits. 
Kamala Harris or Donald Trump.
Whoever wins, there’s one thing that’s been increasingly playing on my mind.
The Americanisation of British politics.
The race between Donald Trump and Kamala Harris is so polarised. Two people – and two groups of supporters – so certain they are right and the other side is wrong – disagreeing so fundamentally on pretty much everything.
And the tone of the debate too… the violence of the language… the two tribes on social media becoming ever more entrenched.
It feels like it’s happening here too. 
And it’s reflected in the media as well. America has long had opinionated news outlets… there’s no Ofcom requiring impartiality in TV media… and big brand media personalities espousing their own views.
You can see the trend towards that in the United Kingdom too… with more partisan outlets and media influencers. 
It’s not necessarily a bad thing… everyone has their bias, maybe it’s good if people are open about it. But it does change the tone of the debate. And it does mean that as a news consumer, if you prefer to have your own views amplified rather than challenged – that’s easier.

Video 👇

text:
This year, I find myself without any predictions for how things will unfold tomorrow. Instead, I am left with a sense of unease. 

In 2016, I felt the energy that Trump brought to the campaign and was confident he would win. At that time, I was teaching in the Caribbean. The university organized a debate ahead of each election, but this time they could not find anyone willing to advocate for Trump. So that task ultimately fell to me. It was actually quite a lot of fun. Feels like such an innocent time looking back at it now. 

I was so certain of Trump's victory that instead of watching the election results come in on election night, I watched a Breaking Bad marathon. By around 1 a.m., it became clear that Trump had won.

At the time, I was completely unaware of the sinister forces coalescing to undermine him. I had no idea that the FBI had spent months pursuing Trump on fake charges, nor would I have believed it if someone had told me. I had no idea that Obama would hamstring Trump with the fraudulent Intelligence Community Assessment, nor that they would throw everything at him for the next four years.

By 2020, I had grown more cynical, yet in hindsight, I was probably still quite naive. I had a negative feeling about that election, both instinctively and objectively, primarily because Trump pretty much outsourced things to a complete fraud, Fauci, who undermined him at every turn.

Consequently, I was less engaged than I had been in 2016. I anticipated intelligence community interference, such as the fraudulent Hunter Biden letter. However, what I was still naive about was the extent of the election shenanigans regarding counting being stopped, ballot harvesting, late-night ballot drops, and so forth. I thought I had become quite hardened by four years of anti-Trump hoaxes, but the entire election situation was truly eye-opening.

Now, four years later, I look back and feel quite disillusioned. Objectively, Trump should win. The early numbers look promising, the polls are favorable, and other indicators, such as dissatisfaction with the current administration, also favor him. Yet, on a visceral level, I can't get myself to feel the same enthusiasm I felt in 2016. The innocence is gone.

Given everything that has transpired—from the fraudulent Russia collusion narrative to the numerous fabricated cases against Trump—surely, they are not going to allow him to simply walk back into the White House? I wish I didn't feel this way, but looking back at the past eight years, how can one not feel this way?
